{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":16903,"name":"","username":"godan","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/godan/{size}/49_2.png","created_at":"2017-03-28T15:52:55.087Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI‚Äôm working on a volume renderer for 3D textures (that start life as a bunch of 2D textures). Here is what I‚Äôve got so far, using the Stanford Volume dataset. Super creepy \u003cimg src=\"/images/emoji/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg src=\"//cdck-file-uploads-global.s3.dualstack.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/1X/bed175ad9291db0db1babb84f84acd11c1927425.jpg\" width=\"690\" height=\"370\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://gist.github.com/danhambleton/f318a91405c36aef15dc4cda4e93c451\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003eHere is the source\u003c/a\u003e (for Urho OpenGL) and \u003ca href=\"http://prideout.net/blog/?tag=volume-rendering#raycasting\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003ehere is my reference\u003c/a\u003e. I think the biggest challenge is how to integrate it with the rest of the scene‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-03-28T15:52:55.087Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":153,"reads":79,"readers_count":78,"score":857.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":2966,"topic_slug":"volume-shader-for-3d-textures","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://gist.github.com/danhambleton/f318a91405c36aef15dc4cda4e93c451","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Volume render for 3D Texture ¬∑ GitHub","clicks":43},{"url":"http://prideout.net/blog/?tag=volume-rendering#raycasting","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"volume rendering at The Little Grasshopper","clicks":33},{"url":"https://discourse.urho3d.io/t/volumetric-rendering/2713/4","internal":true,"reflection":true,"title":"Volumetric Rendering","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":4}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":134,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":16918,"name":"","username":"dragonCASTjosh","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dragoncastjosh/{size}/774_2.png","created_at":"2017-03-29T06:19:47.461Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eIm not sure your intention with making this but it would be cool to extend this out into fog and other volumetric based effect. Ill have to look deeper into your implementation out of a pure curiosity POV as i was looking to implement volume rendering as part of my graphics additions, I was intending to base it mainly from frostbites publication as i loved the results. This may also be interesting for you to look at: \u003ca href=\"https://www.shadertoy.com/view/MdlyDs\"\u003ehttps://www.shadertoy.com/view/MdlyDs\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYour solution looks to be more of the data visualisation side. For example medical scans but that may just be from the images.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-03-29T06:19:47.461Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":72,"readers_count":71,"score":24.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":2966,"topic_slug":"volume-shader-for-3d-textures","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.shadertoy.com/view/MdlyDs","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Shadertoy BETA","clicks":39}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":284,"hidden":false,"trust_level":3,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":16929,"name":"","username":"godan","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/godan/{size}/49_2.png","created_at":"2017-03-29T12:50:57.936Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSo, yes, I wrote this with a more data-viz/science application in mind. However, I think the approach is general enough for wider applications. Although this particular implementation is not super polished, there are a couple good tricks in there:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe shader operates through a material applied to bounding box. This means that apart from some occlusion stuff, it should ‚Äúfit‚Äù in to the rest of the scene.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAgain, since it is a material applied to a box, textures, lighting, and (possibly) shadows should be pretty simple to integrate.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIt has a couple fancy moves to reduce slice artifacts (half stepping, and some ray jitter).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWould be interesting to hear what use cases there might out there. I guess smoke/liquids is an obvious one‚Ä¶\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-03-29T12:50:57.936Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":67,"readers_count":66,"score":23.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":2966,"topic_slug":"volume-shader-for-3d-textures","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":134,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":16967,"name":"Jonathan","username":"Sinoid","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png","created_at":"2017-03-31T04:06:31.448Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eHow dense is your volume? Looks quite nice, pretty jealous that I can‚Äôt get away with raytracing volumes as I have to merge poly-soup via CSG and smooth the seams.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-03-31T04:06:31.448Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":61,"readers_count":60,"score":22.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":2966,"topic_slug":"volume-shader-for-3d-textures","display_username":"Jonathan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":669,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false}],"stream":[16903,16918,16929,16967]},"timeline_lookup":[[1,2066],[2,2065],[4,2063]],"suggested_topics":[{"id":7099,"title":":fallen_leaf: Polynomials \u0026 Harmonics","fancy_title":":fallen_leaf: Polynomials \u0026amp; Harmonics","slug":"polynomials-harmonics","posts_count":6,"reply_count":0,"highest_post_number":7,"image_url":null,"created_at":"2021-12-13T05:06:04.641Z","last_posted_at":"2021-12-27T23:27:39.489Z","bumped":true,"bumped_at":"2021-12-27T23:27:39.489Z","archetype":"regular","unse